16,109 British nationals visited Guatemala in 2018. Most visits are trouble free.
Large demonstrations occur throughout Guatemala, including in Guatemala City and other major towns, often with little or no notice. There may be disruptions to traffic and public transport. You should remain cautious, avoid all political demonstrations and monitor local news channels. See Political situation
When travelling in the country, follow the advice of the local authorities (PROATUR) and monitor local media. See Local travel
There is an ongoing outbreak of coronavirus in China and elsewhere in the region. You should comply with any additional screening measures put in place by the Guatemalan authorities. See Health.
On 31 January 2020, the Government of Guatemala announced that those who have visited China within the previous 15 days will not be permitted entry to Guatemala until further notice. This applies to travellers of all nationalities.
On 5th March the President declared “State of Public Calamity” for 30 days in all the territory of Guatemala. The “State of Public Calamity” allows the authorities to take measures to prevent the entry and possible spread of coronavirus (COVID-19). See Entry requirements
On 11 March 2020, Guatemalan authorities announced that from Thursday 12 March 2020 all citizens of Europe, China, Korea and Iran are prohibited from entering Guatemala. This measure was later modified. The new measures introduced from today, 12 March 2020, will prevent people travelling from China, Iran, Korea, Germany, Italy, and Spain from entering Guatemala. If your travel plans will be affected by this announcement, please check with your nearest Guatemalan embassy before travel.
Guatemalan citizens who come from those countries will be able to enter the national territory, but if they have COVID-19 symptoms, they will be quarantined for 7 days in the Specialized Hospital of Villa Nueva, where they will be evaluated under the medical care of trained Doctors. Passengers coming from Panama will be evaluated at the airport and questioned on their recent travel history. Any travel from a COVID infected country or anyone displaying symptoms of Coronavirus will be quarantined at the Villa Nueva Hospital. The government urges the population to remain calm and to stay informed via official channels. They should follow the guidance on preventive measures.
The rainy season in Guatemala normally runs from June to November, coinciding with the hurricane season in the Caribbean. See Rainy season
Guatemala has one of the highest violent crime rates in Latin America. Take care in all parts of the country, including Guatemala City. You should carry personal ID when travelling (certified copies are fine). See Crime
Guatemala has active volcanoes, some prone to heightened activity. See Volcanoes and Natural disasters
Avoid travelling on public buses (repainted US school buses). Private inter-city coach services are safer, but not immune from attack. See Local travel
UK health authorities have classified Guatemala as having a risk of Zika virus transmission. For more information and advice, visit the National Travel Health Network and Centre website
Although there’s no recent history of terrorism in Guatemala, attacks can’t be ruled out. See Terrorism
You can contact the emergency services by calling 120 (police) or 122/123 (ambulance and fire).
If you’re abroad and you need emergency help from the UK government, contact the nearest British embassy, consulate or high commission.
Take out comprehensive travel and medical insurance before you travel.
